@jreback thanks for the quick review.  I will change the function name to read_sas.  

When you mention `to_sas` do you mean to implement a writer?  I wasn't planning to do a writer at this point.  My view is that this is an archaic format and shouldn't normally be used for generating new files.  Note that this is SAS xport, not the native sas7bdat.

In SAS xport files there are only two data types, ASCII text and numeric, which is always double type.  The doubles are stored in an old IBM format which stores a given number of decimal places.  There is sort of a pseudo-integer type when the number of decimals is given as zero.  In the R foreign package these are returned as ints.  We could do that too, but then if there are missing values it would have to go back to double.

@kshedden btw...for the next project!

I think it makes sense to have https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sas7bdat as an optional dep and read this.
(even IIRC its slow / whatever), should be straightforward to drop it into our impl).
